<font color="#FF0000">VETS AND NONVETS</font><br>
<tt>Wed May 28 22:17:12 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I spent one year in 'nam, from oct. 67 to oct. 68. I went because I understood that the government of North Vietnam had broken the peace treaty it made with the French, and was committing agression against the south. To refuse to serve would have been an insult to my Grandfather who served in wwI against German aggression, and my Father who served against Japanese aggression in wwII. When the communists took control of the north, millions of people voted with their feet by walking many miles to the south. They left behind most of their posessions rather than live under communistic rule. But then communism followed them and insisted they would live under its iron hand. I detest the loss of lives, but wonder if this government should have done something more or different to help South Vietnam. Maybe a better plan could have ended the &quot;conflict&quot; more quickly. I had a great deal of mixed emotions when the US troops evacuated. Glad it was over, sad it ended so shamefully. My country which I was so proud of just gave up and went home! It seemed that those who died or were wounded did so in vain. Again thousands left all behind to escape the communist rule. Many died trieing! That should tell you something!!!                                                                      
